Clarifying comments:
This question concerns bound grammatical marking of dual number on nouns. The marker should be on an open set of nouns, not a restricted set. This feature is in contrast to [GB317 Is dual number regularly marked in the noun phrase by a dedicated phonologically free element?
](https://github.com/glottobank/Grambank/wiki/GB317) which focuses on the non-bound marking of dual number. For more on bound marking, please see this [page](https://github.com/glottobank/Grambank/wiki/'on-the-verb-noun'-or-'by-morphology'). If there is only bound marking of number on nouns derived from other word classes (such as adjectives or verbs), that does not suffice for a 1.

Number marking is often fused with other functions, such as definiteness/specificity or gender/noun class. It is possible for the number marker to also signal other functions and be coded as 1, as long as they don't interfere with the distinctions in numbers and as long as number marking is productive and regular.

